<P>
MORNING REPORT: FIRST OFF . . . 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The New York City Opera officially canceled its fall season Thursday and 
threatened the same for its spring program unless striking musicians agree to a 
contract by next month. The 69-member orchestra has been without a contract 
since June 1 and struck on Sept. 13, opening night of the fall season. On 
Saturday, the union voted, 56-4, to reject a pact, and the opera said then that 
the season, scheduled to end Nov. 19, would be canceled if the orchestra 
members did not return. Martin Oppenheimer, the company's vice chairman and 
lead negotiator, said Thursday that "obviously, we are extremely saddened by 
this development because it puts out of work hundreds of innocent people who 
rely on these jobs for their livelihood." John Glasel, president of the union 
local, called the cancellation regrettable and said that the opera management's 
deadline for reaching a contract "exemplifies the Neanderthal negotiating style 
of the company." The opera and its musicians have been divided over wages and 
the number of work weeks that orchestra members are guaranteed annually. 
Musicians earned $755 a week under the old contract. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
