<LENGTH>
<P>
203 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ENROLLMENT INCREASE MARKS TURNAROUND IN GARDEN GROVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
GARDEN GROVE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This year's growth in enrollment at the Garden Grove Unified School District, 
the county's second-largest, has reversed a 20-year downward trend. 
</P>
<P>
And higher birth rates in the areas served by the district indicate that the 
increase in student enrollment will continue, district officials say. 
</P>
<P>
Figures from the district's office of business services show an increase of 561 
students this year over last school year, bringing enrollment to 36,725, a 1.6% 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
The district's enrollment peaked in the 1968-69 school year with 53,114, when 
it was then the county's largest district. 
</P>
<P>
A recently released state report examining birth rates projected large 
increases in California's school enrollment. District information officer Alan 
Trudell said that birth rates in the cities the district serves -- Garden 
Grove, and portions of Santa Ana, Westminster, Fountain Valley, Stanton, 
Cypress and Anaheim -- indicate that growth in the district is expected to keep 
going up. 
</P>
<P>
The latest data available shows that in 1987 Garden Grove's birth rate was 19.5 
per 1,000, while for Santa Ana, which provides 25% of the district's children, 
the birth rate was 33.9 per 1,000, nearly twice the county average, Trudell 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
