<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: REAL ESTATE; 
</P>
<P>
FIGURES POINT TO DROP IN CONSTRUCTION OF HOMES AND APARTMENTS IN 1989 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by MICHAEL FLAGG, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It looks as if construction of new homes and apartments will be down in Orange 
County this year. That is the tale new figures from the Construction Industry 
Research Board tell. 
</P>
<P>
As of August, with a third of 1989 left, builders had obtained building permits 
for just 11,534 units. Last year -- for the entire year -- builders obtained 
23,455; the year before they got 24,698. 
</P>
<P>
Permits are an approximate indicator of construction activity because most 
units are built within a few months of obtaining a permit. Here is how this 
year's permits break down through August: Houses accounted for 5,903 permits, 
while such attached housing as condominiums and apartments totaled 5,631. 
</P>
</TEXT>
